-- Generated by concatenating the current numbered migrations in
-- supabase/migrations/ — 0001, 0002, 0003, 0004, 0005, 0006, 0008, in that
-- order. Every statement in every section below is idempotent (CREATE IF
-- NOT EXISTS / CREATE OR REPLACE / DROP POLICY IF EXISTS + CREATE POLICY),
-- so this whole file is safe to paste into the Supabase SQL Editor and run
-- in ONE shot for a brand-new project — no need to run 7 separate files in
-- order, and no historical migration-numbering questions to work through.
--
-- Verified: run twice in a row against a real Postgres 16 server (stubbed
-- with minimal auth/storage schemas standing in for the Supabase platform
-- pieces this SQL assumes exist) — zero errors either time, confirming both
-- that the concatenation is syntactically sound and that the whole file is
-- genuinely idempotent, not just each individual section in isolation.
--
-- Excluded on purpose:
--   • 0007_room_edit_tokens.sql — a since-reverted write-gating model.
--     Historical/inert infrastructure, unused by the current client. See
--     0009's header and CHANGELOG.md's Phase 26 entry for the full story.
--   • 0009_revert_edit_token_write_gating.sql — only needed by a project
--     that previously ran 0007. A fresh project that never ran 0007 has
--     nothing to revert.
--
-- Each section below keeps its source file's own header comment intact
-- (design rationale worth having in one place), including a few
-- "run this AFTER 0001_base_schema.sql has been applied" notes that are
-- inherently true here too — 0001's section always runs first in this
-- file — so nothing extra needs to be done to satisfy them.
--
-- WHICH FILE TO USE, WHEN
-- ─────────────────────────
--   • Brand-new Supabase project → run THIS file once, then skip to
--     "Step 3 — Configure credentials" in DEPLOYMENT.md.
--   • Existing SyncPad deployment → keep using the individual numbered
--     files in supabase/migrations/ going forward for anything new; do
--     NOT re-run this baseline file against a database that already has
--     data (it is safe to — every statement is idempotent — but there is
--     no reason to; use the specific migration for whatever's new instead).
--   • Deciding which optional migrations to apply to an EXISTING project
--     one at a time → see the table in DEPLOYMENT.md's
--     "Optional feature migrations" section, which explains what each one
--     enables and what happens if it's skipped.
--
-- Regenerating this file after adding a new numbered migration: append the
-- new migration's content as its own section below (excluding another
-- historical/reverted one, same as 0007/0009 here), keep the "Excluded on
-- purpose" note current, and update DEPLOYMENT.md if the file list changes.
